User Manual for Othello/Reversi Game

1. Introduction

This is a web-based version of the Othello game. In this game the human (us) play with dark pieces, meanwhile AI, our opponent, plays with lights. The project is implemented using Python, Flask and JSON for game state storage. 
This manuel.doc explains how to install important elements, run the application, and play Othello Game. 
Please go to the READ.md file, where flowcharts, technical documentation and the detailed descriptions of the code modules are described.


2. Requirements for the game system

Python 3.8 (or any other later version)
A web browser such as Chrome or Safari
Flask library


3. Instruction for installation

Download or clone the provided Othello/Reversi game to your computer; if you downloaded a .zip archive, unzip all files to a folder before proceeding.

In this project directory, open the terminal.

Install the required libraries using pip. For example: pip install Flask.

The Othello game project should include the folders:	

	img_flowcharts (folder with flowcharts images of the loops used in the Python code)

	static/style.css (for web interface)

	templates/index.html (for web interface)

The project of Othello game should include the files:	

	flask_ai_opponent.py (the main Python code)

	config.py (contains constants and settings used by the game, like DARK, LIGHT, NONE, 		SAVE_FILE, and SECRET_KEY. This makes the game easy to reuse and adjust.)

	othello_game.log (automatically created log file that records human moves, AI opponent 		moves, illegal move attempts, turn changes, and game save/load events. You can review 		this file to track game progress or debug issues.)

	finished_product.json (it is used to save and load game progress)

	README.md (technical documentation)

	manual.doc (detailed user instructions)


4. How to run the game

In the folder open the terminal.

By writing python flask_ai_opponent.py, start the Flask server.

The game creates othello_game.log in the project folder, recording moves, illegal attempts, turn changes, and save or load events for tracking or debugging.

You will see the URL (in most cases it is highlighted by blue).

Open this URL in a web browser, where you will see the Othello game.


5. How to play instruction

Goal: the player needs to have more pieces of their colour than the AI opponent when the game finishes. The game finishes when the board is full or when both players have no legal moves.

Your role as a player: to give you an advantage, you are playing with dark pieces which start first in the game.

Make your move; click on the square where you want to place your piece; you can place your piece only when it is legal (frames one or more of the opposition’s pieces in between another of your token), otherwise if move is illegal, it will not let you move to that square and will prompt a message and the turn will go to AI opponent.

AI opponent: AI opponent plays with light pieces and after the player's move it will choose moves randomly from all available legal options. If the AI has no legal moves, the turn will go back to the player. Whenever you make a move, illegal moves, AI opponent moves, and the current player turn are recorded in othello_game.log.

Move Rules: a move must frame at least one opponent piece, this is called outflanking. All outflanked pieces are flipped to your color automatically.

Game Ends: the game ends when the board is full or there are no possible legal moves for both players. The player with the most pieces wins, after the win the message is displayed, which tells the winner or if there is a tie.


6. Saving and Loading Games

Save Game: to save the game, click on the save button below the board to store the current game state in finished_product.json. This will save the current display of board, turn, and remaining moves. 

Load Game: to load the game, click on the load button also below the board to restore a previously saved game. The game will continue from the last saved state, but if no saved game exists, a message will be displayed. Game saves and loads are also recorded in othello_game.log, so if a load fails because the JSON file is missing, it is logged as an error.


7. The use of the Command Line and API

These functions and routes allow a developer or user to create a different GUI using the existing game backend:
The game logic is separated into Python these functions:

initialise_board()
normalise_board(board)
in_range(r, c)
move_is_legal(player, position, board)
moves_are_legal(player, board)
make_move(player, position, board)
count_pieces(board)
ai_turn(board)

Flask routes:

/ – Home page, which shows the board and the game status.
/game – Handles human move submission (POST).
/save_game – Saves the current game to a JSON file.
/load_game – Loads a previously saved game from a JSON file.

Logging: All moves, illegal attempts, turn changes, and save or load events are recorded in the file othello_game.log and in the folder automatically. This file can be used to debug, track game progress, or integrate with other tools. 
The functions are available for developers to create new GUIs, AI bots, or automated tests.


8. The web interface of the game

Board display: Shows an 8×8 board with pieces.
Current turn: Displays which player’s turn it is.
Move counter: Tracks remaining moves.
Flash messages: Inform you about illegal moves, AI moves, and game status.
Save and load buttons: Allow you to save or continue a game.


